Certainly! Here is a simple "Hello World" program in C++:

```
#include <iostream>

int main()
{
    std::cout << "Hello, World!" << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This program will output the string "Hello, World!" to the console when run.

The "Hello World" program is already very simple and efficient, so there isn't much room for optimization. However, it is possible to remove unnecessary code and make it even more concise. Here is an even more efficient version of the program:

```
#include <iostream>

int main()
{
    std::cout << "Hello, World!\n";
}
```

This version does not use the `return 0` line of code because it is not necessary in this case. It also replaces `std::endl` with `\n` to avoid flushing the output buffer, which can marginally improve performance in larger programs.

Yes, you are correct! The C `printf` function is generally faster than the C++ `cout` stream, especially when outputting large amounts of data. This is because `printf` uses buffered output, which writes data to the output device in larger chunks, whereas `cout` writes data immediately to the output device. However, in most cases, the difference in performance between the two is negligible for small and moderate amounts of output.

Here's an example of a "Hello, World!" program using `printf` in C++:

```
#include <cstdio>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");
    return 0;
}
```

This program will output the same "Hello, World!" message as before, but with the faster `printf` function.

